<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Twenty-third session 
</b>Agenda item 6 
<b>Universal periodic review 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Report of the Working Group on the Universal 
Periodic Review</b>*<b> 
</b></p>
<p><b>  France 
  Addendum 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Views on conclusions and/or recommendations, voluntary commitments 
and replies presented by the State under review 
</b></p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> * The annex to the present report is circulated as received. 
</p>
<p> United Nations A/HRC/23/3/Add.1
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>General Assembly </b>Distr.: General 
28 May 2013 
English 
Original: French </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/23/3/Add.1 
</b></p>
<p><b>2</b> GE.13-14147 
</p>
<p>1. France is deeply committed to the universal periodic review. This unique process not 
only enables each State to give an account of the measures it has taken to improve the 
human rights situation in its territory and evaluate remaining challenges, but also to share 
examples of good practice and make recommendations to other States. France considers the 
universal periodic review to be an essential tool, whose follow-up and recommendations are 
of a continuing nature. With this in mind, France will submit a midterm report in 2015 on 
the implementation of the recommendations made during the universal periodic review in 
January 2013. 
</p>
<p>2. France has carefully considered the 165 recommendations it received. All of the 
ministers concerned participated in the drafting of the replies to the recommendations and 
the National Consultative Commission on Human Rights was consulted during the process. 
</p>
<p>3. This addendum is divided into several parts. It is supplemented by an annex 
explaining the positions taken by France in respect of each of the recommendations. 
</p>
<p>4. France accepts the recommendations whose wording and intention it supports, as 
well as those it has already implemented. 
</p>
<p>5. France does not accept the recommendations that it is not in a position to implement 
for legal or constitutional reasons, whose content it does not support, or whose claims it 
rejects. 
</p><p>6. France has not responded to the recommendations on subjects that do not fall under 
the scope of the universal periodic review. 
</p>
<p><b>  Legislative and structural framework for the protection of human rights 
</b></p>
<p>7. France <b>accepts</b> the following recommendations: 
</p>
<p>120.2, 120.17, 120.18, 120.19, 120.21. 
</p>
<p>8. France <b>partially accepts</b> the following recommendations: 
</p>
<p>120.5, 120.20. 
</p>
<p>9. France <b>does not accept</b> the following recommendations: 
</p>
<p>120.1, 120.3, 120.4, 120.6, 120.7, 120.8, 120.9, 120.10, 120.11, 120.12, 120.13, 
120.14, 120.15, 120.16, 120.22, 120.43. 
</p>
